    <section class="about-section" id="aboutabout">
        <h3 class="section-header">About</h3>
        <p>Hospital apparatus is usually clunky, bulky, and uncomfortable for the patient. This degrades a patient's experience, possibly impacting their attitude towards treatment, their overall treatment experience, and ultimately both their mental and physical health. Furthermore, such equipment is difficult to carry around, clean, and maintain by hospital staff, and the handling of said equipment can cause injuries and significantly lower energy levels. </p>
        <p>Apollon, designed by  the renowned design firm Adaption, partnering with leading healthcare startup SkyLabs, has announced a groundbreaking wearable device. Apollon can measure oxygen saturation, temperature, and respiration rate in real time; these functions are all packaged into a sleek, small, user-centric device composed of a ring and wristband connected by a flexible wire. The design incorporates a detachable, easy-to-clean silicone cover that fits various finger sizes comfortably, ensuring fit for a diverse range of patients. </p>
        <p>Apollon’s design is made up of a ring and wristband connected by a flexible wire. The wristband (itself made of easy-to-clean removable silicone) display allows users to check their health data, and the battery, previously found in the ring, has been moved to the wristband. This improves wearing comfort and enables longer usage. In addition, the single-sized silicone ring around the sensor module provides comfort, as well as allowing users of varying finger sizes to wear it comfortably. </p>
